            "story": "Louis Roederer “Cristal”  2006\nChampagne, FR\n\n55% Pinot Noir, 45% Chardonnay\n\nThis wine was created in 1876 at the behest of Tsar Alexander II, who asked Louis Roederer to save his best cuvee annually.  He also asked that the bottle be clear in order to show off the wine’s fantastic color or, according to popular mythology, to expose any poison or explosive devices that might be hidden within the bottle.  Alexander II also asked that the bottle be flat-bottomed to demonstrate the high quality of the crystal used in the bottle—the punt adds strength to the bottle so that the pressure of the champagne does not cause the bottle to explode—or, also according to legend, so that an explosive device could not be hidden under the bottle.  Regardless, the wine took its name from its crystal bottle.  \n\n \"Fantastic from the start. A colossal power of beautiful rumbling Pinot maturity. It's like chewing on the ripest grapes from Ay and Verzenay. At the same time ultra stylish: unmistakable Cristal essence of peach and mango sweetness, pineapple, coconut, vanilla, sprightly acidity and citrus blossom. \n\n95 points from Wine Spectator",
