            "year": "2012",
            "bin_number": "142",
            "story": "Chianti Colli Senesi (Le Ragnaie)(Tuscany, Italy) 2012.  100% Sangiovese.  \n\nChianti Colli Senesi is produced in the hills around Siena in Tuscany, central Italy. It is one of the seven sub-zones incorporated as part of the Chianti DOCG, including Chianti Colli Fiorentini, Chianti Colline Pisane, Chianti Montalbano, Chianti Montespertoli, Chianti Rufina andChianti Colli Aretini.\n\nThe grapes come from the highest part of the Ragnaie vineyard, above the 600 meter threshold that the government slaps on Brunello and Rosso di Montalcino production. Thus the grapes must be declassified. This is very sexy Chianti with an alluring nose of red cassis and sour cherries. The palate continues with radiance and bright fruit wrapped around a tight skeletal structure.\n\nRiccardo and Jennifer Campinoti purchased the property with a mix of old vines and younger plantings. The estate spreads accross 42 acres, 12 acres of which are in the zone where the cellars are based, Le Ragnaie itself. These vines are the highest of any in Montalcino, some reaching above the DOCG mandated 1,960 feet above sea level.  As one of the highest points in the region it became famous for bird catchers, in fact the traditional birdcatchers' net features on the label as part of the winery's logo. The estate takes its name from the fact that this net looked rather like a spider's web (Ragna, in Italian).\n\nOrganic viticulture is employed, grapes are hand picked, de-stemmed, fermented and then aged in large 25 hl Slavonian oak casks for 36 months. The high vineyards of Ragnaie that form the basis of the blend plus the long, gentle macerations result in enormously charming, aromatic and really quite high toned wines that still manage to retain the requisite power.\n",
